{"cursor":"42110","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\n'Genetic drift' or 'allelic drift' is the change in the frequency of a gene\nvariant (allele) in a population due to random sampling. {{Cite journal\n| volume = 21 pages = R837âR838 author = Masel J title = Genetic drift journal =\n| Current Biology year = 2011 doi = 10.1016/j.cub.2011.08.007 url =\n| http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0960982211008827 issue=20\n| pmid = 22032182\n}} The alleles in the offspring are a sample of those in the parents, and\nchance has a role in determining whether a given individual survives and\nreproduces. A population's allele frequency is the fraction of the copies of one\ngene that share a particular form. {{cite book\n  | last = Futuyma first = Douglas authorlink = title = Evolutionary Biology\n  | publisher = Sinauer Associates series = year = 1998 doi = isbn = 0-87893-189-\n  | 9 page = Glossary}} Genetic drift may cause gene variants to disappear\n  | completely and thereby reduce genetic variation.\n\nWhen there are few copies of an allele, the effect of genetic drift is larger,\nand when there are many copies the effect is smaller. Vigorous debates occurred\nover the relative importance of natural selection versus neutral processes,\nincluding genetic drift. Ronald Fisher held the view that genetic drift plays at\nthe most a minor role in evolution, and this remained the dominant view for\nseveral decades. In 1968 Motoo Kimura rekindled the debate with his neutral\ntheory of molecular evolution, which claims that most instances where a genetic\nchange spreads across a population (although not necessarily changes in\nphenotypes) are caused by genetic drift. {{cite book\n  | last = Futuyma first = Douglas authorlink = title = Evolutionary Biology\n  | publisher = Sinauer Associates series = year = 1998 doi = isbn = 0-87893-189-\n  | 9 page = 320}}\n","linknr":788,"url":"Genetic_drift","recorded":1362483308,"links":64,"instances":["mathematics","mathematics","population_genetics","statistics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Population genetics","Evolutionary biology","Genetic genealogy"],"headings":["Analogy with marbles in a jar","Probability and allele frequency","Mathematical models of genetic drift","Drift and fixation","Genetic drift versus natural selection","Population bottleneck","History of the concept","See also","Notes","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/94/Symbol_support_vote.svg/15px-Symbol_support_vote.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/CollapsedtreeLabels-simplified.svg/200px-CollapsedtreeLabels-simplified.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Tree_of_life.svg/16px-Tree_of_life.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/48/Folder_Hexagonal_Icon.svg/16px-Folder_Hexagonal_Icon.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a8/Office-book.svg/16px-Office-book.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0b/Random_sampling_genetic_drift.svg/550px-Random_sampling_genetic_drift.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/6/1/761d03d58fddb5ed09161ea72690362e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/6/4/d64c082b833ecf5da40a5e2280d35ceb.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/6/c/46c20877df1660d9bd03e3b2577f87f3.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/5/d/35d32db82ec43264fc39cdca28dbeeb2.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/d/c/3dca4bce23cee968e0839c2a3169cc09.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/Random_genetic_drift_chart.png/250px-Random_genetic_drift_chart.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/f/3/0f3ebbf9ed2a279f8ae0a94c1300001e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/3/c/c3c84f6d71d5835fca52e47477c7f287.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/a/1/da1066c05d1d5bc9bd747ff460ada3d7.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/0/1/901c85b